ce:section.ce:para:
The sensor based on Val-GQDs was used for quantitative detection of Hg2+ under the optimized conditions. Fig. 11
                         displays the fluorescent response of the sensor in different concentration of Hg2+ and calibration plot of Hg2+ concentration vs. corresponding maximum fluorescence intensity. As shown in Fig. 6, the fluorescence intensity will rapidly decrease with the increase of Hg2+ concentration. When Hg2+ concentration is in the range from 0.8nM to 1μM, the fluorescent quenching efficiency linearly decreases with the increase of Hg2+ concentration. The linear equation was F=−0.7328C+0.9623, with statistically significant correlation coefficient of 0.992, which F is the fluorescence intensity at 450nm and C is Hg2+ concentration. The detection limit was found to be 0.4nM that was obtained from the signal-to-noise characteristics of these data (S/N=3). The sensitivity is comparable with or obviously higher than that of other optical sensors based on GQDs for detection of Hg2+ (Table 1
                        ). And it is lower than the maximum level for the mercury in drinking permitted by the US Environmental Protection Agency (2ppb, 10nM).
